{"actual_usd":0.12409,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":177,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"No—always the Son.\" *I rub a thumb along a dried streak of clay on my apron, thinking how often people mistake a thing being revealed for a thing being made.* \"His baptism wasn't the moment he became God's Son or became divine. It was a showing, a public naming—like the sun coming through cloud, not the sun being lit.\"\n\n*I shift my weight against the bench, the morning air cool at my sleeves.* \"As Christians have said it, Jesus is eternally the Son—he didn't start being divine at Bethlehem, or in the Jordan, or anywhere else. He took on flesh in time, yes, but he did not begin to be God in time. If you want, I can tell you how the baptism, the incarnation, and verses like 'today I have begotten you' all fit together without getting knotted.\"","rolling_24h_usd":32.89526500000002,"run_id":"b8151221-e667-4d02-aac0-3e7a5676a498"}
